Package structures.vectors

The core linear (vector-like) data structures in computer science.
  • Stack
  • Queue
  • List
Each structure has 2 implementations - an array, and linked-list implementation. Ultimately, the the run time for basic operations such as insertion, and deletion has O(1) constant runtime for both implementations.

The advantage for array implementations is that accessing and updating the array is generally faster than accessing and updating a linked-list because of the overhead associated with allocating space for a new node object.

However, once, the internal array becomes full, we must copy all elements to a new array. This is an expensive operation, but fortunately is does not happen often, as the list size is doubled after each re-allocation. This means we can expect an expensive insert to occur approximately log2(n) times for n elements. So for a list of size 1 Million, we will only have to reallocated about 20 times.

The disadvantage to the array approach is implementation. Using nodes allows the implementation to be considerably simpler to implement, and thus less error-prone.

From the outside perspective, they behave exactly the same. Therefore, they can be used interchangeably. The may have slightly different public methods as they are inheriting public methods from different places. But, if instantiated with an interface (good practice) like Stack stack = new ArrayStack(); or Stack stack = new LinkedStack();, the two objects will behave identically.

  • Interface Summary 
    Interface Description
    List<T>
    Abstract List structure.
    Queue<E>
    Concrete implementations of Queue data structures will implement this interface.
    Stack<E>
    Concrete implementations of Stack data structures will implement this interface.
    Vector<T>
    Interface for all linear DataStructures such as LinkedList, ArrayList, or any other vector-like data structure.
  • Class Summary 
    Class Description
    ArrayList<E>
    Basic implementation of a generic ArrayList.
    ArrayQueue<E>
    Implementation of Queue using an internal array to hold data elements.
    ArrayStack<E>
    Implementation of Stack using an internal array to hold data elements.
    LinkedList<T>
    Basic implementation of Doubly Linked List
    LinkedList.Node<T>
    Node class for chaining together keys in a LinkedList
    LinkedQueue<K>
    Basic FIFO LinkedQueue implementation.
    LinkedStack<T>
    Basic implementation of a LinkedStack class using a Linked List.
    List.ListIterator<T>
    Static Iterator class so that the List can be iterated on via the enhance for loop.
